{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496510"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1373"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1373"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.27,0.01,0.71,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30915"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1852"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a three month history of painless swelling of her left arm (Image). She does not have any current health issues, but had a left mastectomy and axillary clearance for carcinoma 18 months ago. A review six months ago was normal. She is not taking any medications and has no allergies. She had a rainforest holiday in Malaysia about four months ago and can remember getting mosquito bites on her arms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable apart from the uniform swelling of her left arm. The swelling is non-tender and compressible but the indentation quickly disappears.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Lymphatic filariasis","Recurrence breast cancer","Post-surgery lymphoedema","Deep venous thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features that consist with \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-surgery lymphoedema\u003C/strong\u003E. This disorder occurs when lymphatic intake exceeds the ability to remove lymph, thus accumulating in the interstitial space. This commonly occurs in surgeries which involve removal of the lymph nodes, which decreases lymphatic flow, such as mastectomy with axillary clearance. Post-surgical lymphedoema typically presents with unilateral swelling in the the region of previous surgery and is usually describing as non-pitting, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with warmth, erythema and tenderness of the skin which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphatic filariasis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a helminthic infection which affects the lymphatic system. Although recent travel in Asia may be suggestive of this diagnosis, this disease typically presents with fever, painful lymphadenopathy and lymphangitis. The incubation period and development of lymphoedema may take 12 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erecurrence of breast cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in this case as local or axillary recurrence may obstruct lymphatic flow. This is less likely in this case as there is no mention of an axillary lump that might suggest recurrence. Any suspicion for recurrence would warrant imaging to exclude this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep venous thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E also presents with unilateral swelling but is typically a more acute clinical picture accompanied by erythema. Furthermore, deep venous thrombosis typically occurs in the lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Slowly progressive, unilateral swelling in the same ipsilateral limb of limb node dissection is suggestive of post-surgical lymphedema."],"references":["Executive Committee of the International Society of Lymphology. The diagnosis and treatment of peripheral lymphedema: 2020 Consensus Document of the International Society of Lymphology. Lymphology. 2020;53(1):3-19. PMID: 32521126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30915"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1373"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19659"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19659"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ce16078e-3021-48c3-9cb5-0ef617bb19c8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ce16078e-3021-48c3-9cb5-0ef617bb19c8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30915"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-24T20:00:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-24T20:00:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta